<div class=3D"text">

<p>Given below is a simple algorithm for computing the Sun's angular
coordinates to an accuracy of about 1&nbsp;arcminute within two centuries
of 2000.  The algorithm's accuracy degrades gradually beyond its four-centu=
ry
window of applicability.  This accuracy is quite adequate for computing, fo=
r=20
example, the times of sunrise and sunset, or solar transit.  For navigation=
al
purposes it would provide about 1&nbsp;nautical mile accuracy. The algorith=
m=20
requires only the Julian date of the time for which the Sun's coordinates a=
re=20
needed (<a href=3D"https://aa.usno.navy.mil/data/docs/JulianDate.php">Julia=
n dates</a> are a form of=20
<a href=3D"https://aa.usno.navy.mil/faq/docs/UT.php">Universal Time</a>.)</=
p>

<p>First, compute D, the number of days and fraction (+&nbsp;or&nbsp;=E2=80=
=93)
from the epoch referred to as "J2000.0", which is 2000 January 1.5,
Julian date 2451545.0:</p>

<div class=3D"center formula">
   D =3D JD =E2=80=93 2451545.0
</div>

<p>where JD is the Julian date of interest.  Then compute</p>

<table style=3D"margin: 1em 0;" class=3D"center formula">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left" valign=3D"top">Mean anomaly of the Sun:</td><=
td align=3D"left" valign=3D"top">g =3D 357.529 + 0.98560028 D</td></tr>
<tr><td align=3D"left" valign=3D"top">Mean longitude of the Sun:</td><td al=
ign=3D"left" valign=3D"top">q =3D 280.459 + 0.98564736 D</td></tr>
<tr><td align=3D"left" valign=3D"top">Geocentric apparent ecliptic=20
     longitude<br> of the Sun (adjusted for aberration):</td>  =20
     <td align=3D"left">L =3D q + 1.915 sin g + 0.020 sin 2g</td></tr>
</tbody></table>

<p>where all the constants (therefore g, q, and L) are in degrees. It may=
=20
be necessary or desirable to reduce g, q, and L to the range 0=C2=B0 to=20
360=C2=B0.</p>

<p>The Sun's ecliptic latitude, b, can be approximated by=20
b=3D0. The distance of the Sun from the Earth, R,=20
in astronomical units (AU), can be approximated by</p>

<div class=3D"center formula">
   R =3D 1.00014 =E2=80=93 0.01671 cos g =E2=80=93 0.00014 cos 2g
</div>

<p>Once the Sun's apparent ecliptic longitude, L, has been computed, the
Sun's right ascension and declination can be obtained.  First compute the=
=20
mean obliquity of the ecliptic, in degrees:</p>

<div class=3D"center formula">
   e =3D  23.439 =E2=80=93 0.00000036 D
</div>

<p>Then the Sun's right ascension, RA, and declination, d, can be obtained=
=20
from</p>

<div class=3D"center formula">
     tan RA =3D cos e sin L / cos L<br>
     sin d =3D sin e sin L
</div>

<p>RA is always in the same quadrant as L.  If the numerator and=20
denominator on the right side of the expression for RA are used in a=20
double-argument arctangent function (e.g., "atan2"), the proper quadrant=20
will be obtained.  If RA is obtained in degrees, it can be converted to=20
hours simply by dividing by 15.  RA is conventionally reduced to the range
0h to 24h.</p>

<p>Other quantities can also be obtained. <a href=3D"https://aa.usno.navy.m=
il/faq/docs/eqtime.php">The=20
Equation of Time</a>, EqT, apparent solar time minus mean solar time, can=
=20
be computed from</p>

<div class=3D"center formula">
EqT =3D q/15 =E2=80=93 RA
</div>=20

<p>where Eqt and RA are in hours and q is in degrees.  The angular=20
semidiameter of the Sun, SD, in degrees, is simply</p>=20

<div class=3D"center formula">
SD =3D 0.2666 / R
</div>

<p>This algorithm is essentially the same as that found on page C5 of=20
<a href=3D"https://aa.usno.navy.mil/publications/docs/asa.php"><i>The Astro=
nomical Almanac</i></a>; a=20
few constants have been adjusted above to extend the range of years for=20
which the algorithm is valid.</p>

<p>Graphs of the angular error of this algorithm can be viewed by clicking=
=20
on the links below.  Each PDF graph shows the difference in arcseconds=20
between this algorithm and an accurate reference ephemeris, as a function o=
f=20
year.  The reference ephemeris is DE405 from the Jet Propulsion Laboratory.=
</p>

<div style=3D"margin: 0.5em 1em 0.5em 4em;">
<a href=3D"https://aa.usno.navy.mil/graphics/sun_lonlat.pdf">Ecliptic coord=
inates (PDF, 254K)</a> =E2=80=93
longitude (red) and latitude (green)<br>

<a href=3D"https://aa.usno.navy.mil/graphics/sun_radec.pdf">Equatorial coor=
dinates (PDF, 283K)</a> =E2=80=93
right ascension (red) and declination (green)
</div>


<div class=3D"sectionheading">Other Sources:</div>

<p>If the algorithm given here is not sufficiently accurate, other=20
easy-to-implement ephemerides of the Sun (along with those of the Moon and=
=20
major planets) can be found in:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Chapront-Touze, M. &amp; Chapront, J. 1991,=20
  <i><a href=3D"http://www.willbell.com/math/mc9.htm" target=3D"_blank">Lun=
ar=20
  Tables and Programs from 4000 BC to AD 8000</a></i> (Richmond, VA: =20
  Willmann-Bell, Inc.)</li>
  <li>Bretagnon, P. &amp; Simon, J-L 1986,=20
  <i><a href=3D"http://www.willbell.com/math/MC11.htm" target=3D"_blank">Pl=
anetary=20
  Programs and Tables from =E2=80=934000 to +2800</a></i> (Richmond, VA: Wi=
llmann-Bell,=20
  Inc.)</li>
</ul>

<p>
Alternatively, the <a href=3D"https://aa.usno.navy.mil/software/mica/micain=
fo.php">Multiyear Interactive=20
Computer Almanac (MICA)</a>, an application for PCs and Macs, computes coor=
dinates=20
of the Sun, Moon and planets to better than 0.1-arcsecond accuracy. It prov=
ides=20
almanac data in tabular form, at any time interval, for the years 1800 thro=
ugh 2050.</p>


